  "texts": [
    "On the Anscombean view, this wider context is a part of what someone does when it exhibits the distinctive teleological microstructure brought out by the reason-eliciting sense of the question 'Why?'.",
    "In this case, both the goals towards which the action is targeted (performing some recognisable cognitive function) and the norms that apply to its performance (which rule out invalid answers to the question and 'deviant causal pathways') place it in the special category presupposed by our talk about cognitive phenomena.",
    "So, if offloading is a pervasive and transformative feature of human cognition, then this should lead us to accept that these actions and their constitutive environmental context are part of what mark creatures like us out in the landscape of information processing systems as the kind of cognitive agents we are.",
    "Resistance to this picture can come from a way of thinking about agency and the environment that Anscombe rejects.",
    "While we would be right to reject a view that holds bare movements either of the body or of putative external resources to be cognitive, the proposal is that cognition is constitutively dependent on actions; and that actions are not identical with these movements abstracted from their context."
  ],
